{{Short description|Intellectual movement and framework}}
{{Use American English|date=June 2021}}
{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2021}}
[[File:Critical race theory book display.jpg|thumb|A book display with works said to be on critical race theory]]

'''Critical race theory''' ('''CRT''') is a cross-disciplinary examination, by [[social movement|social]] and [[Civil and political rights|civil-rights]] scholars and activists, of how [[law in the United States|laws]], social and political movements, and media shape, and are shaped by, [[Social constructionism|social conceptions]] of [[Race and ethnicity in the United States census|race and ethnicity]]. Goals include challenging all mainstream and "alternative" views of [[racism]] and [[racial justice]], including [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]], [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] and [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]]. The word ''critical'' in the name is an academic reference to [[critical thinking]], [[critical theory]], and scholarly [[criticism]], rather than criticizing or blaming people.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Iati |first=Marisa |date=29 May 2021 |title=What is critical race theory, and why do Republicans want to ban it in schools? |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2021/05/29/critical-race-theory-bans-schools/#LRM3F7NVEZBNREQT2IV7RD3BGI |quote=Rather than encouraging White people to feel guilty, [[Kendall Thomas|Thomas]] said critical race theorists aim to shift focus away from individual people’s bad actions and toward how systems uphold racial disparities.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kahn |first=Chris |date=2021-07-15 |title=Many Americans embrace falsehoods about critical race theory |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/many-americans-embrace-falsehoods-about-critical-race-theory-2021-07-15/ |access-date=2022-01-22}}</ref> 

CRT is also used in sociology to explain social, political, and legal structures and power distribution as through a "lens" focusing on the concept of race, and experiences of [[Racism in the United States|racism]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Christian |first1=Michelle |last2=Seamster |first2=Louise |last3=Ray |first3=Victor |date=2019-04-16 |title=New Directions in Critical Race Theory and Sociology: Racism, White Supremacy, and Resistance |url=https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/0002764219842623 |journal=American Behavioral Scientist |volume=63 |issue=13 |pages=1731–1740 |doi=10.1177/0002764219842623 |s2cid=151160318 |issn=0002-7642}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last1=Yosso |first1=Tara |title=The Blackwell Companion to Social Inequalities |last2=Solórzano |first2=Daniel G |year=2005 |editor-last=Romero |editor-first=Mary |chapter=Conceptualizing a critical race theory in sociology}}</ref>  For example, the CRT [[conceptual framework]] examines racial bias in laws and legal institutions, such as highly disparate [[United States incarceration rate|rates of incarceration]] among racial groups in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Borter |first=Gabriella |date=2021-09-22 |title=Explainer: What 'critical race theory' means and why it's igniting debate |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/legal/government/what-critical-race-theory-means-why-its-igniting-debate-2021-09-21/ |access-date=2022-01-22}}</ref> A key CRT concept is [[intersectionality]]{{emdash}}the way in which different forms of inequality and identity are affected by interconnections of race, class, gender, and disability.{{sfn|Gillborn|2015|p=278}} Scholars of CRT view race as a [[social construct]] with no biological basis.{{sfn|Curry|2009a|p=166}}<ref name="Gillborn 2020">{{cite book |last1=Gillborn |first1=David |title=SAGE Research Methods Foundations |last2=Ladson-Billings |first2=Gloria |date=2020 |publisher=SAGE Publications |isbn=978-1-5264-2103-6 |editor1=Paul Atkinson |series=Theoretical Foundations of Qualitative Research |chapter=Critical Race Theory |doi=10.4135/9781526421036764633 |editor2=Sara Delamont |editor3=Alexandru Cernat |editor4=Joseph W. Sakshaug |editor5=Richard A. Williams |display-editors=1 |s2cid=240846071}}</ref> One tenet of CRT is that racism and disparate racial outcomes are the result of complex, changing, and often subtle social and institutional dynamics, rather than explicit and intentional prejudices of individuals.<ref name="Gillborn 2020" />{{r|Iati}}{{sfn|Bridges|2019}} CRT scholars argue that the [[Social constructionism|social and legal construction]] of race advances the interests of [[White people]]{{sfn|Curry|2009a|p=166}}{{sfn|Ruparelia|2019|pp=77-89}} at the expense of people of color,<ref name="Milner 2013">{{cite journal |last1=Milner |first1=Richard |date=March 2013 |title=Analyzing Poverty, Learning, and Teaching Through a Critical Race Theory Lens |journal=Review of Research in Education |volume=37 |issue=1 |pages=1–53 |doi=10.3102/0091732X12459720 |issn=1935-1038 |jstor=24641956 |s2cid=146634183}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Crenshaw|1991}}; {{harvnb|Crenshaw|1989}}.</ref> and that the [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal notion]] of U.S. law as "neutral" plays a significant role in maintaining a racially unjust social order,{{sfn|Ansell|2008|pp=344–345}} where formally [[Color blindness (race)|color-blind]] laws continue to have [[racially discriminatory]] outcomes.{{sfn|Crenshaw|2019|pp=52–84}}

CRT began in the United States in the [[post–civil rights era]], as 1960s landmark civil rights laws were being eroded and [[School segregation in the United States|schools were being re-segregated]].<ref name="The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica">{{cite encyclopedia |title=Critical race theory |date=September 21, 2021 |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/critical-race-theory |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211122165350/https://www.britannica.com/topic/critical-race-theory |archive-date=November 22, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Ansell|2008|pp=344–345}}; {{harvnb|Bridges|2019|p=7}}; {{harvnb|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|p=xiii}}.</ref> With [[Racial inequality in the United States|racial inequalities persisting]] even after civil rights legislation was enacted, CRT scholars in the 1970s and 1980s began reworking and expanding [[critical legal studies]] (CLS) theories on class, economic structure, and the law<ref>{{harvnb|Ansell|2008|p=344}}; {{harvnb|Cole|2007|pp=112–113|ps=: "CRT was a reaction to Critical Legal Studies (CLS)&nbsp;... CRT was a response to CLS, criticizing the latter for its undue emphasis on class and economic structure, and insisting that 'race' is a more critical identity."}}</ref> to examine the role of U.S. law in perpetuating racism.{{sfn|Bridges|2021|loc=2:06}} CRT, a framework of analysis grounded in [[critical theory]],{{sfn|Crenshaw|Gotanda|Peller|Thomas|1995|p=xxvii|ps=. "Indeed, the organizers coined the term 'Critical Race Theory' to make it clear that our work locates itself in intersection of critical theory and race, racism and the law."}} originated in the mid-1970s in the writings of several American legal scholars, including [[Derrick Bell]], Alan Freeman, [[Kimberlé Crenshaw]], [[Richard Delgado]], [[Cheryl Harris]], Charles R. Lawrence III, [[Mari Matsuda]], and [[Patricia J. Williams]].{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=344}} CRT draws from the work of thinkers such as [[Antonio Gramsci]], [[Sojourner Truth]], [[Frederick Douglass]], and [[W. E. B. Du Bois]], as well as the [[Black Power]], [[Chicano]], and [[radical feminist]] movements from the 1960s and 1970s.{{sfn|Ansell|2008|p=344}}

Academic critics of CRT argue it is based on [[storytelling]] instead of evidence and reason, rejects truth and merit, and [[Anti-liberalism|opposes liberalism]].<ref name="The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica"/><ref>{{harvnb|Cabrera|2018|p=213}}.</ref> Since 2020, conservative U.S. lawmakers have sought to [[2020s controversies around critical race theory|ban or restrict the instruction]] of CRT along with other [[Critical pedagogy|critical]] education in [[Primary school|primary]] and [[secondary school|secondary schools]],{{r|Iati|Wallace-Wells}} as well as relevant training inside federal agencies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/09/04/politics/trump-administration-memo-race-training-ban/index.html |title=Trump bars 'propaganda' training sessions on race in latest overture to his base |author=Caroline Kelly |website=CNN}}</ref> Advocates of such bans argue that CRT is false, [[Anti-Americanism|anti-American]], villainizes White people, promotes [[Left-wing politics|radical leftism]], and indoctrinates children.<ref name="The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica"/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Duhaney |first=Patrina |date=2022-03-08 |title=Why does critical race theory make people so uncomfortable? |url=http://theconversation.com/why-does-critical-race-theory-make-people-so-uncomfortable-176125 |access-date=2022-03-15 |website=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]] |language=en}}</ref> Advocates of bans on CRT have been accused of misrepresenting the tenets and importance of CRT and of having the goal of broadly silencing discussions of racism, equality, social justice, and the history of race.<ref name="Bump 2021">{{Cite news |last=Bump |first=Philip |title=Analysis {{!}} The Scholar Strategy: How 'critical race theory' alarms could convert racial anxiety into political energy |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/06/15/scholar-strategy-how-critical-race-theory-alarms-could-convert-racial-anxiety-into-political-energy/ |date=June 15, 2021 |issn=0190-8286 |url-access=limited |archive-date=June 22, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210622025034/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2021/06/15/scholar-strategy-how-critical-race-theory-alarms-could-convert-racial-anxiety-into-political-energy/ |url-status=}}</ref>{{sfn|Harris|2021}}

