In his introduction to the comprehensive 1995 publication of critical race theory's key writings, [[Cornel West]] described CRT as "an intellectual movement that is both particular to our postmodern (and conservative) times and part of a long tradition of human resistance and liberation."{{sfn|West|1995|p=xi}} 

Law professor Roy L. Brooks defined critical race theory in 1994 as "a collection of critical stances against the existing legal order from a race-based point of view".{{sfn|Brooks|1994|p=85}}

In 2005, [[Tara J. Yosso]] described CRT as a "framework that can be used to theorize, examine and challenge the ways race and racism implicitly and explicitly impact on social structures, practices and discourses".{{sfn|Yosso|2005|pp=70–71}}

[[Gloria Ladson-Billings]], who{{emdash}}along with co-author William Tate{{emdash}}had introduced CRT to the field of education in 1995,{{sfn|Ladson-Billings|Tate|1995}} described it in 2015 as an "interdisciplinary approach that seeks to understand and combat race inequity in society."{{sfnm |1a1=Gillborn |1y=2015 |1p= |2a1=Ladson-Billings |2y=1998 |2p=}} Ladson-Billings wrote in 1998 that CRT "first emerged as a counterlegal scholarship to the positivist and liberal legal discourse of civil rights."{{sfn|Ladson-Billings|1998|p=7}}

In 2017, [[University of Alabama School of Law]] professor [[Richard Delgado]], a co-founder of critical race theory, and legal writer [[Jean Stefancic]] define CRT as "a collection of activists and scholars interested in studying and transforming the relationship among race, racism, and power".<ref>{{harvnb|Cabrera|2018|p=211}}; {{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|2017|p=3}}.</ref>

In 2021, [[Khiara Bridges]], a law professor and author of the textbook ''Critical Race Theory: A Primer'',{{sfn|Bridges|2019}} defined critical race theory as an "intellectual movement", a "body of scholarship", and an "analytical toolset for interrogating the relationship between law and racial inequality."{{sfn|Bridges|2021|loc=2:06}}

The 2021 ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica|Encyclopaedia Britannica]]'' described CRT as an "intellectual and social movement and loosely organized framework of legal analysis based on the premise that race is not a natural, biologically grounded feature of physically distinct subgroups of human beings but a socially constructed (culturally invented) category that is used to oppress and exploit people of colour."<ref name="The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica"/> In the video that accompanies the article, CRT is defined as a "way of thinking about the world, especially the social norms and legal practices that govern society".<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)">{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Examine critical race theory (CRT) |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia Britannica |date= |url=https://www.britannica.com/video/225205/what-is-critical-race-theory |id=Video with transcript |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211124003959/https://www.britannica.com/video/225205/what-is-critical-race-theory |archive-date=November 23, 2021 |url-status=}}</ref>

''[[Education Week]]'' described the core of CRT as the idea that race is a [[Social constructionism|social construct]] and [[racism]] is neither an individual bias nor prejudice{{emdash}}it is "embedded in the legal system" and supplemented with policies and procedures.<ref name="Sawchuk 2021">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.edweek.org/leadership/what-is-critical-race-theory-and-why-is-it-under-attack/2021/05 |title=What Is Critical Race Theory, and Why Is It Under Attack? |first=Stephen |last=Sawchuk |date=May 18, 2021 |access-date=November 10, 2021 |magazine=Education Week |url-access=limited}}</ref>

==Tenets==
Scholars of CRT say that race is not "biologically grounded and natural";{{sfn|Curry|2009a|p=166}}<ref name="Gillborn 2020" /> rather, it is a socially constructed category used to oppress and exploit people of color;<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/> and that racism is not an aberration,{{sfn|Bell|1992}} but a normalized feature of American society.<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/> 
According to CRT, negative stereotypes assigned to members of minority groups benefit white people<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/> and increase racial oppression.{{sfn|McCristal-Culp|1992|p=1149}}
Individuals can belong to a number of different identity groups.<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/> The concept of [[intersectionality]]{{emdash}}one of CRT's main concepts{{emdash}}was introduced by legal scholar Kimberlé Crenshaw.{{sfnm |1a1=Hancock |1y=2016 |1p=192 |2a1=Crenshaw |2y=1989 |2p=}}

[[Derrick Bell|Derrick Albert Bell]] Jr. (1930 – 2011), an American lawyer, professor, and [[civil rights activist]], writes that racial equality is "impossible and illusory" and that racism in the U.S. is permanent.{{sfn|Bell|1992}}
According to Bell, civil-rights legislation will not on its own bring about progress in race relations;{{sfn|Bell|1992}} alleged improvements or advantages to people of color "tend to serve the interests of dominant white groups", in what Bell calls "interest convergence".<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/> These changes do not typically affect{{emdash}}and at times even reinforce{{emdash}}racial hierarchies.<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/> This is representative of the shift in the 1970s, in Bell's re-assessment of his earlier desegregation work as a civil rights lawyer. He was responding to the Supreme Court's decisions that had resulted in the re-segregation of schools.{{sfnm |1a1=Cesario |1y=2008 |1pp=201-212 |2a1=Bell |2y=1980 |2p=}}

The concept of [[standpoint theory]] became particularly relevant to CRT when it was expanded to include a [[black feminist]] standpoint by [[Patricia Hill Collins]]. First introduced by feminist sociologists in the 1980s, standpoint theory holds that people in marginalized groups, who share similar experiences, can bring a collective wisdom and a unique voice to discussions on decreasing oppression.{{sfnm |1a1=Harnois |1y=2010 |1p= |2a1=Collins |2y=2009 |2p=}} In this view, insights into racism can be uncovered by examining the nature of the U.S. legal system through the perspective of the everyday lived experiences of people of color.<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/>

According to ''Encyclopedia Britannica'', tenets of CRT have spread beyond academia, and are used to deepen understanding of socio-economic issues such as "poverty, police brutality, and voting rights violations", that are impacted by the ways in which race and racism are "understood and misunderstood" in the United States.<ref name="Examine critical race theory (CRT)"/>

== Common themes ==
