[[File:ABSS Board Meeting (2021 Aug 23) - Anti critical race theory protester.jpg|thumb|A protester speaks against critical race theory at a [[Alamance-Burlington School System]] board meeting in 2021]]
In early 2021, [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]-backed bills were introduced to restrict teaching critical race theory in public schools in several states,<ref name="O'Kane">{{cite web |last=O'Kane |first=Caitlin |title=Nearly a dozen states want to ban critical race theory in schools |date=May 21, 2021 |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/critical-race-theory-state-bans/ |archive-date=June 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210613004743/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/critical-race-theory-state-bans/ |url-status=live |website=CBS News}}</ref> including [[Idaho]], [[Iowa]], [[Oklahoma]], [[Tennessee]] and [[Texas]].<ref name="Waxman">{{cite news |last1=Waxman |first1=Olivia |title='Critical Race Theory Is Simply the Latest Bogeyman.' Inside the Fight Over What Kids Learn About America's History |url=https://time.com/6075193/critical-race-theory-debate/ |magazine=Time |date=24 June 2021 |url-access=limited}}</ref> Several of these bills specifically mention "critical race theory" or single out ''The New York Times''{{'}} [[1619 Project]]. CRT is only taught at a [[university]] level, though some lower-level curricula have reflected basic themes of CRT.{{r|Iati}}<ref name="The Editors of Encyclopaedia Britannica"/>{{Example needed|s|date=November 2021}}

In mid-April 2021, a bill was introduced in the [[Idaho Legislature]] that would effectively ban any educational entity from teaching or advocating "[[sectarianism]]", including critical race theory or other programs involving social justice.<ref name="Richert">{{cite web |last1=Richert |first1=Kevin |last2=Jones |first2=Blake |date=April 19, 2021 |title=Legislative roundup, 4.19.21: New bill targets sectarianism, critical race theory |url=https://www.idahoednews.org/legislature/legislative-roundup-4-19-21-a-bill-targeting-instruction-on-sectarianism-surfaces/ |website=Idaho Education News |archive-date=April 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210419204506/https://www.idahoednews.org/legislature/legislative-roundup-4-19-21-a-bill-targeting-instruction-on-sectarianism-surfaces/ |url-status=live}}</ref> On May 4, 2021, the bill was signed into law by Governor [[Brad Little]].<ref name="Adams B">{{cite web |last=Adams |first=Biba |url=https://news.yahoo.com/bill-banning-critical-race-theory-124451511.html |title=Bill banning critical race theory in public schools becomes law |work=Yahoo News |date=May 4, 2021 |archive-date=May 6, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210506205741/https://news.yahoo.com/bill-banning-critical-race-theory-124451511.html |url-status=live}}</ref> On June 10, 2021, the [[Florida Board of Education#Ruling|Florida Board of Education unanimously voted]] to ban public schools from teaching critical race theory at the urging of governor [[Ron DeSantis]].<ref name="Postal">{{cite web |last=Postal |first=Leslie |title=Florida board votes to ban critical race theory from state classrooms |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=June 10, 2021 |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/education/os-ne-critical-race-state-board-20210610-7pzv23n7rjeixi3a4veffugalq-story.html |archive-date=June 12, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210612150641/https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/education/os-ne-critical-race-state-board-20210610-7pzv23n7rjeixi3a4veffugalq-story.html |url-status=live}}</ref> As of July 2021, 10 U.S. states have introduced bills or taken other steps that would restrict teaching critical race theory, and 26 others were in the process of doing so.<ref name="Schwartz">{{Cite news |last=Schwartz |first=Sarah |date=2021-06-11 |title=Map: Where Critical Race Theory Is Under Attack |url=https://www.edweek.org/policy-politics/map-where-critical-race-theory-is-under-attack/2021/06 |url-status=live |access-date=2021-07-13 |website=Education Week}}</ref><ref name="Greenfield">{{cite web |last=Greenfield |first=Nathan M. |date=June 12, 2021 |title=Why are states lining up to ban critical race theory? |url=https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20210612085115831 |url-status=live |website=[[University World News]] |archive-date=June 13, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210613232641/https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20210612085115831}}</ref> In June 2021, the [[American Association of University Professors]], the [[American Historical Association]], the [[Association of American Colleges and Universities]], and [[PEN America]] released a joint statement stating their opposition to such legislation, and by August 2021, 167 [[Professional association|professional organizations]] had signed onto the statement.<ref>{{cite web |author1=American Historical Association |author2=American Historical Association |author3=((Association of American Colleges & Universities)) |author4=PEN America |date=June 16, 2021 |title=Joint Statement on Legislative Efforts to Restrict Education about Racism in American History |url=https://www.historians.org/divisive-concepts-statement |access-date=November 23, 2021}} [https://www.historians.org/Documents/News%20and%20Advocacy/2021/Joint%20Statement%20on%20Legislative%20Efforts%20to%20Restrict%20Education%20(1).pdf PDF].</ref> In August 2021, the [[Brookings Institution]] recorded that eight states{{emdash}}Idaho, Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas, Iowa, New Hampshire, Arizona, and South Carolina{{emdash}}had passed regulation on the issue, though also noted that none of the bills that passed, with the exception of Idaho's, actually contained the words "critical race theory". Brookings also noted that these laws often extend beyond race to discussions of [[Gender studies|gender]].<ref name="Ray">{{Cite web |last1=Ray |last2=Gibbons |first1=Rashawn |first2=Alexandra |date=2021-07-02 |title=Why are states banning critical race theory? |url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/fixgov/2021/07/02/why-are-states-banning-critical-race-theory/ |access-date=2021-10-31 |publisher=Brookings Institution}}</ref>

[[Timothy D. Snyder]], historian and professor at [[Yale University]], has called these new state laws ''[[memory laws]]'' — "government actions designed to guide public interpretation of the past". Early memory laws were intended to protect victim groups, such as from revisionism attempts by [[Holocaust denial|holocaust deniers]], but most recently have been used by Russia to protect "the feelings of the powerful", then by Donald Trump's [[1776 Report]] in January 2021, followed by Republican-led legislatures submitting these bills. Snyder called the Idaho version "[[Kafkaesque]] in its censorship: It affirms freedom of speech and then bans divisive speech."<ref name="Snyder">{{Cite news |last=Snyder |first=Timothy |date=2021-06-29 |title=The War on History Is a War on Democracy |work=The New York Times Magazine |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/29/magazine/memory-laws.html |issn=0028-7822 |url-access=limited |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210704024528/https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/29/magazine/memory-laws.html |archive-date=July 4, 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref>

{{As of|December 2021}}, 66 educational gag orders had been filed for the year in 26 state legislatures (12 bills had already been passed into law) that would inhibit teaching any race theory in schools, universities, or state agencies, by teachers, employers or contractors. Penalties vary, but predominantly include loss of funding for schools and institutions. However, in some cases the bills mandate firing of employees.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://pen.org/scope-speed-educational-gag-orders-worsening-across-country/ |title=Scope and Speed of Educational Gag Orders Worsening Across the Country |first=Jeffrey |last=Sachs |date=December 13, 2021 |publisher=PEN America}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://popular.info/p/desantis-proposes-legislation-to |title=DeSantis proposes legislation to let parents sue teachers who tell the truth about U.S. history |first=Judd |last=Legum |author-link=Judd Legum |website=[[Popular Information]] |date=December 20, 2021}}</ref>

On January 15, 2022, his first day in office, governor of Virginia [[Glenn Youngkin]] signed multiple executive orders, including barring the teaching of critical race theory in public schools.<ref name="ExOrd Day1">{{cite news |last=Cain |first=Andrew |title=Youngkin signs executive orders to bar 'critical race theory,' COVID-19 mandates |url=https://richmond.com/news/state-and-regional/govt-and-politics/youngkin-signs-executive-orders-to-bar-critical-race-theory-covid-19-mandates/article_72423217-d285-5946-86f5-5a55274cd7a4.html |work=Richmond Times-Dispatch |date=2022-01-15 |access-date=2022-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Newsroom |first=NBC12 |title=Gov. Youngkin signs 11 executive actions on first day of administration |url=https://www.nbc12.com/2022/01/15/gov-youngkin-signs-11-executive-actions-first-day-administration/ |access-date=2022-01-17 |website=www.nbc12.com |language=en}}</ref>

== Subfields ==
Within critical race theory, various sub-groupings focus on issues and nuances unique to particular ethno-racial and/or marginalized communities. This includes the intersection of race with disability, ethnicity, gender, sexuality, class, or religion. For example, disability critical race studies (DisCrit), critical race feminism (CRF), Jewish Critical Race Theory (HebCrit,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rubin |first=Daniel Ian |date=2020-07-03 |title=Hebcrit: a new dimension of critical race theory |url=https://doi.org/10.1080/13504630.2020.1773778 |journal=Social Identities |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=499–514 |doi=10.1080/13504630.2020.1773778 |s2cid=219923352 |issn=1350-4630}}</ref> pronounced "Heeb"), Black Critical Race Theory (Black Crit), Latino critical race studies (LatCrit<ref>{{harvnb|Yosso|2005|p=72}}; {{harvnb|Delgado|Stefancic|1998b}}.</ref>), Asian American critical race studies (AsianCrit{{sfn|Yosso|2005|p=72}}), South Asian American critical race studies (DesiCrit{{sfn|Harpalani|2013}}), Quantitative Critical Race Theory (QuantCrit<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Castillo |first1=Wendy |last2=Gillborn |first2=David |date=2022-03-09 |title=How to "QuantCrit:" Practices and Questions for Education Data Researchers and Users |url=https://edworkingpapers.com/ai22-546 |language=en}}</ref>) and American Indian critical race studies (sometimes called TribalCrit{{sfn|Yosso|2005|p=72}}). CRT methodologies have also been applied to the study of white immigrant groups.{{sfn|Myslinska|2014a|pp=559–660}} CRT has spurred some scholars to call for a second wave of [[whiteness studies]], which is now a small offshoot known as Second Wave Whiteness (SWW).{{sfn|Jupp|Berry|Lensmire|2016}} Critical race theory has also begun to spawn research that looks at understandings of race outside the United States.{{sfn|Myslinska|2014b}}<ref>See e.g., {{harvnb|Levin|2008}}.</ref>

=== Disability critical race theory ===
Another offshoot field is [[Disability studies#Race|disability critical race studies]] (DisCrit), which combines [[disability studies]] and CRT to focus on the [[Intersectionality|intersection]] of disability and race.{{sfn|Annamma|Connor|Ferri|2012}}

=== Latino critical race theory ===

Latino critical race theory (LatCRT or LatCrit) is a research framework that outlines the social construction of race as central to how people of color are constrained and oppressed in society. Race scholars developed LatCRT as a critical response to the "problem of the [[Color line (racism)|color line]]" first explained by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]].{{sfn|Treviño|Harris|Wallace|2008}} While CRT focuses on the Black–White paradigm, LatCRT has moved to consider other racial groups, mainly [[Chicana/o studies|Chicana/Chicanos]], as well as [[Latinos/as]], [[Asian people|Asians]], [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]/[[First Nations in Canada|First Nations]], and women of color.

In ''Critical Race Counterstories along the Chicana/Chicano Educational Pipeline'', [[Tara J. Yosso]] discusses how the constraint of POC can be defined. Looking at the differences between [[Chicano|Chicana/o]] students, the tenets that separate such individuals are: the intercentricity of race and racism, the challenge of [[dominant ideology]], the commitment to [[social justice]], the centrality of [[Experiential knowledge|experience knowledge]], and the [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] perspective.{{sfn|Yosso|2006|p=7}}

LatCRTs main focus is to advocate social justice for those living in [[social exclusion|marginalized communities]] (specifically Chicana/os), who are guided by structural arrangements that disadvantage people of color. [[Institution|Social institutions]] function as [[Dispossession, oppression and depression|dispossessions]], [[Disfranchisement|disenfranchisement]], and discrimination over minority groups, while LatCRT seeks to give voice to those who are [[victimized]].{{sfn|Treviño|Harris|Wallace|2008}} In order to do so, LatCRT has created two common themes:

First, CRT proposes that white supremacy and racial power are maintained over time, a process that the law plays a central role in. Different racial groups lack the voice to speak in this [[civil society]], and, as such, CRT has introduced a new critical form of expression, called the ''voice of color''.{{sfn|Treviño|Harris|Wallace|2008}} The voice of color is narratives and storytelling [[monologue]]s used as devices for conveying personal racial experiences. These are also used to counter [[metanarrative]]s that continue to maintain [[racial inequality]]. Therefore, the experiences of the oppressed are important aspects for developing a LatCRT analytical approach, and it has not been since the rise of slavery that an institution has so fundamentally shaped the life opportunities of those who bear the label of criminal.

Secondly, LatCRT work has investigated the possibility of transforming the relationship between [[law enforcement]] and racial power, as well as pursuing a project of achieving racial emancipation and anti-subordination more broadly.{{sfn|Yosso|2005}} Its body of research is distinct from general critical race theory in that it emphasizes immigration theory and policy, language rights, and accent- and national origin-based forms of discrimination.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2001|p=6}} CRT finds the experiential knowledge of people of color and draws explicitly from these lived experiences as data, presenting research findings through storytelling, chronicles, scenarios, narratives, and parables.{{sfn|Yosso|2006}}

=== Asian critical race theory ===
Asian critical race theory looks at the influence of race and racism on Asian Americans and their experiences in the U.S. education system.<ref name="Iftikar 2018">{{Cite journal |last1=Iftikar |first1=Jon S. |last2=Museus |first2=Samuel D. |date=November 26, 2018 |title=On the utility of Asian critical (AsianCrit) theory in the field of education |journal=International Journal of Qualitative Studies in Education |volume=31 |issue=10 |pages=935–949 |doi=10.1080/09518398.2018.1522008 |s2cid=149949621}}</ref> Like Latino critical race theory, Asian critical race theory is distinct from the main body of CRT in its emphasis on immigration theory and policy.{{sfn|Delgado|Stefancic|2001|p=6}}

===Critical philosophy of race===
The Critical Philosophy of Race (CPR) is inspired by both Critical Legal Studies and Critical Race Theory's use of interdisciplinary scholarship. Both CLS and CRT explore the covert nature of mainstream use of "apparently neutral concepts, such as merit or freedom."{{sfn|Alcoff|2021}}

